The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | City cops get Lashkar scout
                                                                                                               City cops get Lashkar scout
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                               
	New Delhi, June 29: A court today ordered Mohammad Umer Madni, the alleged Lashkar-e-Toiba talent scout held in Delhi early this month, to be handed over to Calcutta police in a fake notes case.        
	Officials of the capitals Tihar jail, where the associate of Lashkar founder Hafiz Saeed is being held in judicial custody, have been told to hand him over on transmit remand for being taken to Calcutta.         
	Madni, 50, has to be produced before the additional chief metropolitan magistrate of Bankshall Court in Calcutta on or before July 1.        
	Calcutta polices special task force had sought his custody in a case relating to the seizure of fake currency notes amounting to Rs 60,000.        
	Four persons picked up with the fake notes had revealed that Madni was their associate, Calcutta police had said in their custody petition. Mohibur Rahman, Tofazzel Hossain, Ram Dhiraj Ram and Ajit Kumar were nabbed from Beadon Street in Calcutta on May 7.         
	Madni, a resident of Bihar who also acquired Nepalese citizenship, was arrested near the Qutab Minar in Delhi on June 4.                                                                                                                                                                            
